This deck takes a new approach to Fabled and utilizes the new Fabled support along with the Fiendsmith strategy in order to control the game by looping their new boss monster, Fabledswarm Leverzebul.

Leverzebul has the ability to steal your opponents' monsters without targeting. But most notably, he is a soft once per turn. This means that you can loop his effect by constantly reviving him with Fiendsmith's Agnumday, Lacrima the Crimson Tears, Fabled Treason, and A Bao A Qu, the Lightless Shadow. This will usually be supported with combos and interruptions offered by the Fiendsmith and Unchained monsters.

 

So we know what the deck is aiming to accomplish, but how is it being facilitated? In this deck, the Fableds and its tutors take advantage of the fotrunate typing and attribute of their monsters to support a Fiendsmith control/Fiend link style deck. The best method of doing this is to make Fabled Gamygyn, which gets you the full Fiendsmith Fabled combo by itself.

You will be typically trying to turbo this out using Rescue Cat, The Fabled Behillmoth with another level 2, or through certain combo lines using Tour Guide From the Underworld. If you are unable to find this card, you will most likely not be making Leverzebul and will focus on the other engines within your deck.

These cards are your best starters, and all of them unlock something very unique that Fabled has not had before now: linear 1(.5) card combos! Any of the aforementioned starters will end you on a board of an untargetable Leverzebul, A Bao, Treason, and Abominable Chamber, with Lacrima able to revive the Agnumday in the GY. 

Due to this more modern approach of deckbuilding, the deck can fit 9-12 slots of non-engine. This obviously isn't a lot, but it's a big improvement from the previous 0-3 slots that were available.

 

There is a lot of potential for the future of Fabled when it's able to take full advantage of an engine as powerful as Fiendsmith. Good luck going X-2 at locals!

Some Tips

You can send Elemental HERO Neos and Elemental HERO Necroshade from your hand to the graveyard with the effects of Phoenix Wing Wind Blast, Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin, and Polymerization. Reinforcement of the Army can search for Aqua Dolphin and King of the Swamp can search for Polymerization.

Neos gains 500 attack while Neo Space on the field, which is enough attack to beat most monsters in battle. Neo Space Pathfinder can add Neo Space from your deck or graveyard to your hand. She's also searchable by Reinforcement of the Army and can be used as fusion material for Elemental HERO Divine Neos.

deck_excerpt: The Dark Magician is back in action too!
deck_description:
The Ideal Dragon Tail Starting Play

Requires Dragon Tail Fymena and 2 other Dragon Tail monsters. This combo plays around Nibiru, the Primal Being because it only summons 3 times minimum. The Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can special summon Dragon Tail Mulr from your deck, whose effect allows you to fusion summon a Dragon Tail fusion monster using the monsters from your hand and on your field during the opponent's turn. All the current main deck Dragon Tail monsters can set a Dragon Tail spell or trap from your deck, so any combination of them can start this play.

1. Activate Dragon Tail Fymena's effect to discard her, then fusion summon Dragon Tail Altharion by using the two other Dragon Tail monsters in your hand as material.

2. Activate Altharion's effect to target, then return Fymena and 1 other Dragon Tail monster back to your hand as chain link 1. Activate the effects of the Dragon Tail monsters used as fusion material as chain link 2 and higher. This chain blocking will protect Altharion from Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion. Set Ketu Dragon Tail and Rahu Dragon Tail from your deck. If you already have them, then you can set from your deck Dragon Tail Horn and/or Dragon Tail Flame instead.

3. Activate Ketu Dragon Tail to search for Dragon Tail Lucias.

4. Normal summon Lucias.

5. Use Lucias' effect to search for another Fymena.

6. Link summon the Spirit with Eyes of Blue by using Lucias as link material.

7. Link summon the Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres by using Altharion and Lucias as link material. This will remove the Spirit with Eyes of Blue's special summon lock.

7.5. (Optional) Here you can use Altharion's effect to special summon him back from the graveyard, but he won't do much if you go first. If you're going second then, instead of the Heavenly Spheres route, you can link climb with Altharion and Lucias from Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable to Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians to Accesscode Talker.

8. Activate Rahu Dragon Tail to fusion summon Dragon Tail Gramel by using 1 Fymena in your hand and another Dragon Tail monster in your deck as material. Ideally, you'd use whatever Dragon Tail monster you didn't already fuse with this turn to activate its graveyard effect in the next step.

9. Activate the graveyard effects of the Dragon Tail monsters you recently fused with to set Dragon Tail spells and/or traps from your deck.

Your current board should have a Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres, a Dragon Tail Gramel, a set Dragon Tail Horn, and a set Dragon Tail Flame. You should also have a Dragon Tail Fymena and another Dragon Tail monster in your hand, which will allow you to fusion summon on your opponent's turn. If a Dragon Tail Urgula is in your graveyard, then you can activate its graveyard effect to add a Dragon Tail Lucias from your graveyard to your hand for the following turn. The Heavenly Spheres can bounce a card on the field and summon a Dragon Tail Mulr on your opponent's turn.

On the Primite Engine

The Primate engine allows you to summon the Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres by using only 1 card and allows you to summon to the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon by providing to access the Dark Magician. The Dark Magician + any dragon effect monster like Primite Dragon Ether Beryl or Dragon Tail Pan can fuse to make the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. Primite Lordly Lode can special summon the Dark Magician from your hand, deck, or graveyard, then Imduk the World Chalice Dragon can convert the Dark Magician into a dragon monster. Imduk + Ether Beryl = the Heavenly Spheres. The Heavenly Spheres can special summon Dragon Tail Mulr from the deck, who can fusion summon Dragon Tail Altharion by using itself and another monster in your hand as material. Altharion can then add the Dark Magician from your graveyard to your hand for a future play.

deck_excerpt: We need to go Fast Yusei
"Ame no Murakumo wants to know your location!"
deck_description:
Used the Deck in recent locals. Match ups:
1. Fiendsmith Tenpai : DRAW
2. Ryzeal Fiendsmith : WIN 
3. Yubel Unchained : WIN 
4. Primite Blue-eyes : LOOSE
5. Pure Blue-eyes : WIN

Quick summary:

Diabellstar+Wanted are starters thanks to the new Magistus Chorozo. Ty-Phon is a nice Ultimate Slayer Target. Post ALIN, I predict Maliss will be good so we are keeping the Lancea in the side. I like spell non-engine in this deck, but it should be mentioned this deck searches veiler so it is a decent idea to run at least one. Final Bringer of the End Times is a neat pick cause as you continue to recycle your white forest monsters on your oponent's turn you can turn them into pops with it. As for everything else...

New support is interesting and really opens up a pretty great strategy further. Only issue is the field locks you out of darks, but usually by the time you get to Poplar, you have gone through the Azamina line, this is largely due to the aforementioned Chorozo line. Wanted, Diabell, Deception, Hallowed, Mu Rcielago, Elzette, then go into Chorozo, Elzette and synchro to a 6, usually Rciela. This is 6 starters on top of the 9 white forest already had. This gives me the confidence to go over 40, though you can cut down on cards as needed if you want to stick to 40 or cut the Chorozo. The lock is not a big deal because making Chaos Angel or Chimera is not a part of the end board. Cards like Chengying and Executor are not effected by this lock which is really cool... or thematic, whichever one is better.

On the other hand if you start with the deception and a way to Diabellstar, just search the new Diabell cause it's a sinful-spoil card.

Chaos Angel is a bit interesting in this deck, you can make it with a variety of 4s and 6s using Azamina cards and White Forest Synchros. I chose Mudragon as a Super Poly Target so I can change it's attribute to get a max defensive Chaos Angel out, though you may want Garura instead, it would work with the Silvys and Rucia in deck. Guardian Chimera is a really cool addition to this deck and I love the Quickplay fusion alla Chimera Fusion that can really take your opponent by surprise.

As for the Ratios, we are running 3 of the starters then 1 of the cards we wanna find later. You can argue down or out the Astellar, but at that point I would maybe just insert more non-engine like main decking the Super Poly or Drolls. Possibly add a second Tales. Possibly cut some of the field spell as well. 

Overall, I did a few test hands with this and it has not bricked once, it sucks drawing into the white forest one-ofs until you discard them for cost, every card in the deck feels nice cause its very insular and can search and weave between the three engines plus the white forest pitch makes them all useful in some way.

deck_excerpt: Icy Spectacle that is the Icejade Wall.
deck_description:
I tried, and failed; the newer Water support isn't really doing much for the deck as a whole, and I'm not the best duelist / deckbuilder.

Let's face it : in the face of the ever-growing meta, (mostly pure) Icejade can't really keep up. Not like it had a chance in the first place, but you get the point. When combined with the other archetype, the difference in contribution is so great, you better off playing it without trying to implement Icejade's main strategy. However, as my favorite archetype, I will keep experimenting to find the most stable and optimal play / deck while keeping it's member present, keeping in line with, and putting it's general line of play and what makes the deck unique at the forefront.
As such, here's what I've been cooking lately : mish-mash from some of the Icejade variants, powered by Aegirine's depression, Diva adding a card to your opponent's hand, random shark doing their best, some love and care, and finally, a brick made of ice. By channeling Aegirine's rage towards Longyuan, this decklist adopts an all-out attack strategy for when the situation doesn't allow a Lock. We're pushing head on, the same way she jams Aegirocassis straight into Golgonda-Longyuan. The GY revival Icejades have been reduced (I'm so sorry Acti), and Kingfisher is not here (tbf, nver used him again once Rahn hits MD).  

My previous Icejade Deck can be found at : https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/metajade-334563, as a small refresher before this guide.

================== The Cradle

--Main Deck Highlights :

Icejade Aegirine (39354437) : Searches any 1 Icejade S/T upon summon, this includes Icejade Cradle (55343303), meaning you can add any Icejade monster through her. Special summon a Water Monster from hand or GY when targeted for attack or effect, then cannot be destroyed once. Girl watches the whole Icejade family die and single-handedly enables the archetype. Your normal summon #2.

Deep Sea Diva (78868119) : One card to build the Twin Tower Board. Special summons Guitar Gurnards Duonigis (79724755) which in turns banishes your opponent's deck; This is Important to scout out your opponent's deck and determine which synchro you should summon. Your ideal normal summon #1.

Abyss Shark (61496006) : One card ticket for our supporting XYZ play. Adds either Crystal Shark (98881700), which can  be special summoned from the hand or GY at the cost of locking into XYZ, or Dream Shark (6180710), which can also act as an emergency body to tank an attack or effect damage. Unfortunately, we have no way to add him in a consistent way without using our already reserved normal summon.

Crystal Girl (93169863) : Discard target that can be special summoned back from GY to add 1 Level 5 or higher Water from deck at end phase. Use her to extend your board, as she can be used as material for either Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389) or Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) depending on the situation. Add either Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732) to prepare a lock at your next turn, or Icejade Creation Aegirocassis (1295442) to quick effect equip.

White Sardine (98684051) : Used in conjunction with Deep Sea Aria (72060415) to add Deep Sea Diva (78868119) into your hand without using your normal summon. In an emergency, the treated as Tuner effect can be used to summon Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) together with any of the sharks when summoned by Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389).

Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) & Icejade Curse (83670388) : The Icejade's core lock. You might be wondering why the deck only use 1 of each if they are so important. That's because on their own, every one of them is a brick. An Icebrick, if you may. Cenote at 2 is still viable, however, due to it's recycle effect upon activation.

--Extra Deck Highlights :

Deep Sea Prima Donna (50793215) & Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon (30983281) : Two option to go with Diva and Guinard. After banishing your opponent's deck, you can decide wheter it's safe to go into Prima Donna; ADDING 1 OF THOSE BANISHED CARD INTO YOUR OPPONENT'S HAND in order to summon Aegirine (smol) from deck, or summons Accel Synchro to go into either Gymir or Chengying (maybe Baronne if you add her).

Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) : The third option with Diva and Guinard. This is for when you might need something to deal with backrow decks after seeing the opponent's banished card. Luckily, we can summon him with other cards, but it's a bit hard to get them all on field.

N.As.H. Knight (34876719) : Extra interruption to succ your opponent's monster. We XYZ him into his pilot in order to summon Number C101: Silent Honor DARK (12744567) and hopefully go for the win with the extra succ, or go into Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder (90448279) in an emergency.

Worldsea Dragon Zealantis (45112597) : Your Plan B. Field wipes all non-Water after Marincess Coral Anemone (79130389) restriction. Unfortunately, you're always going to need 3 body to summon him. Summoning him means only two things : You are desperate and need the final push to close the game, Or you are seriously fcked. Literally no in-between.

--Side Deck / Extra Plays :
Some cards are not yet available on MD yet.

Surfacing Big Jaws (55697723) & Drake Shark (81096431) : You can add Big Jaws via Abyss Shark (61496006), then add Drake from the summon effect. I use this to summon Bahamut Shark (440556) to summon Xyz Armor Torpedo (94151981) in order to go into the Full Armored Dark Knight Lancer (67630394) line.

Mermail King - Neptabyss (69385019) : Extra layer of protection and interruption that can be summoned for a full board of him, Gymir, Bahamut, & Armored XYZ follow-up if you open with Aegirine (smol) & Abyss-Shark + 1 spare Icejade/Water.

 

================== The Wall

At most, we're going to have 4 scenario going foward, No.1-3 takes off at turn 1; as in we go first :

1. Icejade Wall
The deck's winning condition, and Icejade's signature strategy. Shutting down Your Opponent (not the monsters) from activating effects of monsters depending on the turn they are summoned. When you managed to set this up, you (most of the time) won, except against backrow-focused deck or when they have an out to commit some backrow hate against you.
-- The fabled Icejade Lock is made possible by putting together Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) & Icejade Curse (83670388) + 1 Icejade, preferably Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), in doing so, you locked out your opponent from activating their monster effects, ruining nearly all of their combos,and possibly winning you the game after a long bout of silence and confusion from your opponent. HOWEVER, this lock is Ice-thin for it's Jade-like-quality (lmao), easily broken by removing either Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) or the Icejade body from your board, nulling any advantages you have and probably costing you the game instead. Which is why I propose The Complete Lock, Or as I called it : The Icejade Wall
-- Your normal lock setup + Icejade Erosion (53742162) and one extra Icejade body (Either Aegirine (smol) or Gymir is ideal) completes the lock and turns it into a formidable wall, at which your opponent are helpless against. The negate from erosion should be used to PROTECT THE WALL AT ALL COST, even if that cost is blasting away Gymir and reuniting her with her family.

2. Twin Tower : Gymir - Chengying & Shark Support
Summoning Icejade Gymir Aegirine (86682165) and Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying (96633955), backed up by N.As.H. Knight (34876719) to halt your opponent's offensive. Three interruption that cannot be destroyed by card effects or banished (once Gymir resolves), although keep in mind that Chengying's banish most of the time follows-up from Gymir's, so it's more of a 2.5 interruption. You will be playing around this board most of the time.
-- As we have no way of searching Abyss Shark (61496006), Nash support are not as consistent as the Twin Tower, but can prove game-changing when it hits the field.
-- Do note, in order to summon both Gymir & Chengying using Deep Sea Diva (78868119) alone, YOU WILL BE PUTTING ONE OF YOUR OPPONENT'S BANISHED CARD INTO THEIR HAND and I cannot stress this hard enough, YOUR OPPONENT IS GOING +1 from your line. Of course, if you opens with and could summon Icejade Ran Aegirine (18494511), you can avoid the +1 scenario.
-- Going against backrow decks, prioritize putting Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (9464441) instead of Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying (96633955).
-- Icejade Gymir Aegirine (86682165) Should always be summoned, prioritize her before Chengying except for when you need Dragite more.

3. BrickJade
When a handtrap interrupts you, the last thing to do is hope your opponent bricked as well. At most scenario, best you can do most of the time is a solo Gymir on the board; Worse is a single Deep Sea Diva (78868119) in Attack Position. Consider the surrender button as your option.
-- Priority of Aegirine (smol) search : Cenote / Curse (If either is on hand) >>> Cradle (no Rahn) > Erosion (No Lock, Yes Rahn) = Cenote (Kosmochlor, Yes Rahn; otherwise go for Erosion) > Manifestation (No Lock, Yes Rahn; go second).
-- When unable to put any meaningful board, Aegirine (smol) alone can serve as a good deterrent due to her targeted effect, but don't count on it too much.

4. Second to Go
Either you open with Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle (7142724) and Icejade Kosmochlor (3355732), shutting down you opponent's monsters, handtraps your opponent enough to stop their board, or you try to go into the Twin Tower. If resources are plenty and opponent's interruptions none, Worldsea Dragon Zealantis (45112597) is also a viable way foward. The addition of Sharks can also opens up direct interruption from the XYZ's sucky succ effects.

 

==================

As always, mix and match to suit your style. As the number of new cards increases, I'll try to experiment more in order to find the best way foward for this archetype.

Happy Dueling~

deck_excerpt: Diabellstar and pals is still considered the one of the strongest strategies on Masterduel ladder!
deck_description:
One of the most ridiculously powerful and consistent decks is now available in Masterduel, and that is Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith! Consistency is easily available while Fiendsmith cards turbo out Beatrice, which sends any Snake-Eye starter to the GY (most likely Snake-Eyes Ash) then is revived by Promethean Princess! This is in addition to all the other ways to get to your one card combo via the Azamina cards or through the regular Snake-Eyes starters! This enables the deck to include 19 handtraps, 2 Called By and 1 Crossout while having a very high power ceiling! This means that Snake-Eyes can reliably go first or second, powering through with multiple extenders while handtrapping your opponent to oblivion.

Snake-Eyes Azamina Fiendsmith is undoubtably the most powerful deck on ladder right now, and is perfect if you want to tryhard your way to Masters 1 for those sweet sweet gems.

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Hanko Chow

Tournament: The Side Deck Remote Duel WCQ Regional – April 13th 2025

Placement: 1st Place

The Azamina and Horus archetypes pair well with the Orcust archetype because they both rely on dark monsters for their main plays and can send cards from your hand to the graveyard. The Orcust monsters love the graveyard.

Some Tips

Azamina Ilia Silvia can protect your board from Nibiru, the Primal Being with her omni-negate effect.

Imsety, Glory of Horus + Hapi, Guidance of Horus can make The Zombie Vampire, whose effect can mill Diabellstar the Black Witch or an Orcust monster to extend your plays.

Any level 4 Orcust + a Bystial or an Azamina monster can make a Chaos Angel. Alternatively, Orcust Cymbal Skeleton + Orcust Knightmare, a Chaos Hunter, or Diabellstar the Black Witch can also make a Chaos Angel.

deck_description: Fun Dark Magician deck to use with the new Primite cards. Still occasionally has the classic Dark Magician problem of bricking, but it happens way less with the new cards. Reliably gets Dark Magician out and can sometimes put up a decent fight against some pretty good decks. I am not an expert by any means and I'm not going to claim this is the best DM deck out there (especially since I do not enjoy using Link monsters at all). However, if you want a fun Dark Magician deck to try out that has a semi-classic feel to it, give this one a go and let me know what you think.

deck_name: $10 Structure Starter: The Crimson King [Domain Format]
deck_excerpt: Domain Format: Budget Structure Deck Tune-Ups
deck_description:
The beat drops, and so do they.
This is a beginner-friendly Domain Format list built upon an $11.99 MSRP purchase of the Structure Deck: The Crimson King. It consists of a $10 upgrade of cards purchased from sites like TCGplayer.

Deckmaster: Soul Resonator 
Domain Restrictions: DARK // FIRE // FIEND
Made for Domain Format: Join the Community Discord!

To create this upgrade, please remove these 10 cards and any duplicate cards from the SD: The Crimson King (reference the sidedeck): 
Note: Please also remove the included "Everyone's King" Token

  • ydke://J/o2BMlvswITcYkB8XQiAxVY9wD7V6YEqfQWAvIyWABxbBIC1jxxAtpq3QUtbJwEFKWiAzUULAEZAdoFQBRfAQqs7QCEFhYDkKCjAKSbggAtI/wCdksGBdDN+wKtU3gBOqujAZ8IUgB3n8IDTRUVBA==!dr+1AzqP7wUlk88F8WQyAmzVlAAG3s4EDWg2BdfjOQQoPvED!ofzIBDhR7wL5YqoEOV00ALD7cgQQTWkARBCcBEUm4wDVOD0D3G/IBQ==!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • Structure Deck Full Contents (YGOprodeck)

Next, you will want to buy and add these 38 cards to the deck: 

  • ydke://36vjBe1eaQLFqdoEKCYhAvkyxQAmkEIDe2QdAl06/gJYL/cEiNIjAMWM2wT8b2kEBy8+AnMbUgAVtoYFlcD9AbJDIwDNe4YE44efAlGYPgWgXBkDHvnKA+yPAQBDJZAFaIi1ARimVARO93UBu/qoAAzglQD7mjEDOy/VAV4eSgI=!okk8BRXfCwU7uoUAKwgNApEmyADrqosF!!
  • View on YGOprodeck
  • View on TCGplayer Cart

Additional Resources can be found here:
https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1c8_W7TLHoExz9Iq2yNBKG4kniKN3fjamfMVRehPRitQ/edit?usp=sharing

Domain Format General Rules:

  • Singleton Format: Every card restricted to 1 copy per deck.
  • 60-card Format: Each Main Deck must contain exactly 60 cards.
  • 4-player Pods: Each player competes individually in an all-out battle against three opponents.
  • Deckmaster Restrictions: Each player chooses a "Deckmaster" which dictates the allowed types and attributes for their deck.
  • Deckmaster Contract: A Deckmaster can be summoned from a designated "Deckmaster Zone" using normal summoning rules. After switching zones, Deckmasters may return to the "Deckmaster Zone," where they start the game.

Refer here for additional rules and exceptions:

https://www.domainformat.com/rules 

Broad Categories

This simple strategy has cards that fall into three simple categories:

  • Trap Disruption
  • Boardwipe
  • Revival

Reccommend Combo Guide (from MST.TV):
https://youtu.be/vmcYmR_Nfjo?t=450&si=0vthdhA3ObezcGXX
Please also Reference the Combo Guide Provided on the back of the Paper Playmat.

What do we want our Deckmaster to do? Soul Resonator 
- Start our combos: https://youtu.be/vmcYmR_Nfjo?t=450&si=0vthdhA3ObezcGXX
- Protect our cards when we have Red Dragon Archfiend on field. 
- Find our utility like Labrynth Stovie Torbie or Dark Spirit of Malice 

Soul Resonator, in addition to having a wide domain, can add any LV4 or lower FIEND monster from deck to hand for the cost of locking our Extra Deck summons to DARK Synchros for the rest of the turn. This card was designed premarily to access the Red Dragon Archfiend series of Extra Deck monsters, most notably summoning Red Rising Dragon when sychroed with Bone Archfiend. 

However, that is not all that Soul Resonator can do with its ability to add any low level FIEND monster. This domain deck aims to have it also act as an avenue of access for the powerful Labrynth cards, which can set any trap from our deck, most notably the amazing Red Reign which boardwipes the entire field if used while we have a lv8 Dark Synchro. 

The last portion of Soul Resonator is its ability to banish itself from the GY to protect our cards from destruction while we have Red Dragon Archfiend or a monster whose name becomes Red Dragon Archfiend on our field. This protection is powerful in order to insulate us from boardbreaking attempts, or even to protect us from ourselves when we use Trap boardwipes like Torrential Tribute or Needle Ceiling.

Soul Resonator adds: 

  • Bone Archfiend: Combo Starter
  • Labrynth Stovie Torbie or Labrynth Chandraglier: Labrynth Engine Starter
  • Dark Spirit of Malice or Dark Spirit of Banishment: Revival and Defensive core 
  • Obsessive Uvualoop: Recursive Monster
  • Battle Fader : Battle Prevention 
  • Red Blossoms from Underroot : Synchro Revival

What do we want our Boardwipes to do? 
- Break the Field and our Opponent's Resources
- Show the might of Red Supernova Dragon, Scarred Dragon Archfiend, Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend, and Red Dragon Archfiend!   

The core endboard piece of this deck is Red Supernova Dragon which is able to banish all cards an opponent controls each turn. Because this is a Banish effect, we will hopefully be able to contracct any GY syenrgy or resources our opponents play. 

Addtionally this deck can access the Scarred Dragon Archfiend in the middle of combo, which will destroy all Attack Position monsters an opponent controls. This will allow a fieldwipe in order to take care of any monsters who remain problematic. The other fieldwipes of this deck, Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend and Red Dragon Archfiend also additionally can only destroy monsters. 

Other Boardwipes in the deck, which are in the form of Spells and Traps, are aimed towards breaking our opponent's board in order to allow us to play. 
A notable Spell to point out is Swordsoul Punishment which can be returned to hand by banishing a Synchro from our GY. This is powerful due to Swordsoul Punishment being able to banish any card from the Field or GY, and due to the fact that Red Zone can revive banished Dark Synchro monsters. 

What do we want our Traps to do? 
- Boardwipe
- Disrupt, remove, and Generate Resources

The traps of this deck are premiarly obtained through either Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle or Vision Resonator and provide useful utility. The most powerful of our traps are the ones that mention "Red Dragon Archfiend" or Lv8 Synchros. These traps will provide board removal if their conditions are met. 

Note: Welcome Labrynth will temporarly lock your Extra Deck summons, but most likely it will not be relevent. Welcome Labrynth locks into only being able to summon FIEND from the Extra Deck until the end of the next turn. However, since Domain Format revolves around a 4-turn rotation, you can easily time it so you are not still locked when it returns to being your turn. 

Resources can be generated through the Labrynth Traps when used in conjuction with Labrynth Labyrinth or when used to search Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle. 
Additionally, Red Reign is a reuseuable boardwipe that returns itself to our hand as long as we are constanly Synchro Summoning. 

Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle sets: 

  • Torrential Tribute / Needle Ceiling / Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon : Boardwipes
  • Terrors of the Underroot / Terrors of the Afterroot:  Non-Destructive removal
  • Time to Stand Up : Negate
  • Red Reign : Recursive Boardwipe
  • Big Welcome Labrynth / Welcome Labrynth : Engine Access

Vision Resonator adds:

  • Absolute Powerforce : Battle Protection
  • Scarlet Security : Spell/Trap Removal
  • Crimson Gaia : Engine Access
  • Red Zone : Removal and Revival
  • Fiendish Golem : Monster Removal

What do we want our Revival to do? 
- Revive our powerful Boardwipes!
- Keep our Defenses high

This Red Dragon Archfiend deck has powerful revival tools in the form of Red Zone and Crimson Gaia which are both cards accessible in combo through Vision Resonator. This recursivability allows the deck to weather through calamities and storms while still maintaing board presence. 

Other revival tools in the deck are Dark Spirit of Banishment and Dark Spirit of Malice which can allow you to keep a Labrynth monster on field (though negated) in order to keep defenses high.

Additonally, we can useSoul Resonator to search Red Blossoms from Underroot which can then be used to revive a Synchro from our GY.

Although this deck is a Synchro deck that burns through much of its extra deck, its follow up is impressive in part due to the amount of revival this deck can maintain.

Other Considerations: 

Monsters: Gold Pride - Nytro Head , Dark Hole Dragon , Earthbound Immortal Red Nova + Earthbound Greater Linewalker + Earthbound Servant Geo Kraken , Chaos Dragon Levianeer , D.D. Crow , Vouiburial, the Dragon Undertaker , Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay , Spright Red , Spright Carrot 

Spells: Pot of Avarice 

Traps: Red Screen 

To Recap: 

Important Cards: Red Rising Dragon, Red Supernova Dragon, Red Reign, Crimson Gaia
Strategy Elevator Pitch: Use your powerful Synchros to wipe the board!

Best Upgrades: Bystial Dis Pater, Chaos Angel, Red Lotus King, Flame Crime , Earthbound Prisoner Stone Sweeper 

Start Small. End Big.

deck_excerpt: Conquer the Cyberse safari with these digital beasts!
Got hand trapped? Let's make a deal!
deck_description:
Your Ki-sikil starter was hit with Infinite Impermanence? Don't worry, because now only 1 Ki-sikil monster can start your Evil Twin plays!

The New Support

Any Ki-sikil monster can summon Evil★Twin Ki-sikil Deal. Ki-sikil Deal's effect can send a Lil-la monster from your deck to the graveyard to apply a lingering effect that allows you to draw 1 card each time your opponent activates and resolves an effect in response to your Ki-sikil and Lil-la monster effects. The best Lil-la monster to send from the deck to the graveyard is Live☆Twin Lil-la Sweet because she can special summon herself from the graveyard if you control a Ki-sikil monster. Lil-la Sweet is a good card to have in your hand too, because she can discard herself to negate any card your opponent activates in response to your Live☆Twin card. In short, Ki-sikil Deal can snowball games in your favor and Lil-la Sweet can protect your Live☆Twin starter or Live☆Twin Sunny's Snitch from your opponent's Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, then extend your plays!

The Fiendsmith Connection

This deck could easily access the Fiendsmith engine because most of your Evil★Twin monsters are light fiends. Any light fiend can be used as link material for Fiendsmith's Requiem.

deck_excerpt: Structure deck was actually good? ayo?
deck_description: like a month ago i picked up a couple of the Crimson King structure, here's what I built with it and a handful of other stuff i had lying around

Mostly pure version of Materiactor with a small goblin biker core, mostly so we can play Grand Breakout to dodge handtraps and a big Danger! package as it is both extension for our rank 3 setups and plays nicely with stacking the deck and paying the cost from both Gigadra and Exareptor. 

The Armored Xyz cards are quite good, but I feel that the trap is too bricky in a deck that values every single card it plays and Torpedo is good enough when comboed with Exagard and Meltdown. The body can be later used to summon F0.

Non engine is a bit random for now, but the deck should stay at 40 cards so it can see Materiactors in the opening hand as often as possible and I avoided Imperm as the deck wants to add live interruptions from Exagard to our hand even during the opponent's turn. Bystials are nice as Magnamhut can search any Materiactor if needed.
needs more work but functions well in theory

Dhampir Vampire Sheridan

My first time submission. Sorry for my bad English. So many blue-eyes are in rank match of this season, this deck concept is how to deactivate the gimmiks of the blue-eyes. I've once tried the same concept with more labyrinth gimmik (Arias and Arianna). That was not succeeded because the target of math cannon became higher levels in this season. So I finally give up if the coin is flipped, and kept in mind to increase the winning rate of the first attack. The card criteria for whether to include it or not is whether it has access to other cards, whether it can stop the development against a trendy gimmick with just one card, and if not, whether it can permanently take away resources through exclusion or other ways. Two things I don't like about blue eyes are the latter;

  1. "Beryl" can be used as a link material, while preparing ''Drillbeam".
  2. Adding the extra-summoning right with "Mausoleum". Punishment and Nightmare played an important role for blue-eyes. Punishment can destroy the Beryl itself, and its set-card. This means you can block the extra summoning because the link monster cannot be summoned.
  1. Welcome labyrinth: With some tests, the main cause of the lose at first attack is lack of monster cards. So I included the additional one.
  2. Punishment: I could adopt three cards, but I don't have enough slots in the extra deck. If I have the second one in my hand, they may not work with N'tss, so I adopt two.
  3. Nightmare: Nightmare was another answer for blue-eyes. Since it is not a regular trap, it is not a starting point for the trap recruiting gimmicks. Also, there is no contribution if having second one in my hand , I think two in deck is enough.
  4. Solemn strike: Almost same role with Punishment card. I would like to keep one for Ash protection.

I took top 16 at the April 19th Remote Duel Regional with this (bad) decklist. Ideally you lose the dice roll, win going second and then pick to go second. They will 99% of the time side to go second and go first with charmies in hand while you have handtraps and breakers. 

The changes I would make:

  • No dogwood, you're not going into time. I was scared of maliss lifepoint gain time codidtion, but my Maliss matchups were quick games.
  • Drop Raiho/Ice Barrier package or move Raiho to the side.
  • Gameceil in the main. That card was so good in testing but I didn't have one.
  • Coelacanth/pike?  I didn't have any good non-pike fish targets on hand so I didn't run the fish. Under droll you do posseidra and send shadow squad.
  • Drop the second minstrel or the lancea dragon for a Silent Honor Ark? It can trigger dragoons. 
  • Third teus probably.
A mostly link and synchro deck with a very rare fusion summon.

Dynamic focus points.

 - Counter oriented
 - Viruses for turn 2 hand destruction
 - Rover for stall, lucky double destruction, loop discard resource
 - Closer to midrange floodgate than just control floodgate


Key things to remember:
 - Welcome Labrynth locks SP from deck and extra deck to only fiends, until the end of the next turn. Raider's knight, E-Teleport, and Mask Change II cannot be summoned/used afterwards.
 - Vivid tail GY effect locks activation of the card that turn that is returned to hand. You might want to consider the card that you want to return carefully.
 - Rover's extra deck lock does not apply if you use E-Teleport to SP him.
 - Arianna and Arianne's last effect allows a second attacks by resummoning a monster during battle phase.
 - Rover's effect is not once per turn.

deck_excerpt: Spring erupts with the fires of life!
Skull Invitation FTK ft. Telefon + Emeral + Merchant
deck_description:
Greetings! Are you looking a place for Magical Merchant? With a crafty setup using Telefon, it's now possible. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Special Summon Black Luster Soldier and Kuriboh with their abilities to unlock "Primal Seed" loop. Special Summoning Kuriboh is possible if you play "Silent Graveyard" as Chain Link 2 to disrupt your opponent's GY, where yours doesn't matter.

2) Play "One for One" to Special Summon "Fusion Parasite", which lets you bring forth "The Dark Magicians" if you fuse Parasite + Librarian together. Play "Pot of Generosity" twice to shuffle all Traps back into your Main Deck and use Magicians to draw them and set. Resetting Magicians with Book spells helps you on this point.

3) Play "One for One" to Special Summon "Magical Merchant" and give it to the opponent with "Shien's Spy". When all Traps are ready, activate them and reset Merchant with Book spells.

4) What is going to happen is that Merchant will dig through your opponent's deck until they hit a Spell/Trap and Merchant will stop when it happens. There, 3 x Skull Invitation deals 3 x 300 = 900 damage to them in total for each card sent to the GY. Don't forget to reset Merchant with Book spells until you deal the fatal blow!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning" can be collected by purchasing "Spiral Spear Strike" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

deck_excerpt: Bistro Butcher Mill OTK ft. Telefon + Emeral + Critias
deck_description:
Welcome! Some time ago, I played this deck as Panda and I decided to revise for Telefon. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have drawn your whole Main Deck, Synchro Summon Stardust with Librarian + Telefon and play Burning >>> Broken combo to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1 by activating Burning.

2) Play Black Garden + Legend of Heart to bring forth Critias, which can lead to Garden >>> Critias >>> Chain Summoning combo, if you activate Critias to banish Burning.

3) Bring forth Patrician + Butcher and set all Traps. Here, end your turn and don't forget to discard Wanghu + Wattfox + Shark.

4) When it's Draw Phase of your opponent, activate these Traps in order, with appropriate targets described below:

  1. Back to the Front >>> Wattfox
  2. Give and Take >>> Wanghu
  3. Yang Zing Unleashed

5) What is going to happen is that by destroying Wattfox with Wanghu, your opponent can't do anything. Since their Main Phase 1 is skipped thanks to what was done in #1, with Yang Zing active, they are forced to stick into Battle Phase. Your opponent has to attack with flowers but there is a catch: You can actually choose which monster they would tackle thanks to Patrician. There are two ways you can go with...

  • When your opponent has one flower, direct into Critias to activate Critias and set Front to trigger it. Target Shark to revive, which lets you plant again with Garden.
  • When your opponent's side is full, direct into Bistro to mill your opponent. Keep going until you win the game!

deck_description:
Hey there! This is Telefon version of Panda deck I did back then. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Synchro Summon Omega with Ancient + Telefon and use Auroradon to destroy Omega.

2) Find a way to play "Chain Summoning". If necessary, use "Offerings to the Doomed" along the way to bridge into it. Offerings can be used to destroy Emeral, otherwise Astral Force won't work.

deck_excerpt: Destiny Board Win ft. Telefon + Emeral
deck_description:
Hi! This deck is similar to the one but we will be playing as Telefon. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw until you find these combo pieces: Yata + Droll + Miracle Locus + Disturbance Strategy + Destiny Board + SPYRAL Resort. Activate Resort, set Disturbance + Miracle + Destiny and end your turn by discarding everything but Yata + Droll + Letters. Also, don't forget to use Resort to not deck-out.

2) During your opponent's Standby Phase, activate Miracle to let your opponent draw a card. Then, activate Disturbance and chain into Droll. What will happen is Droll denies for either side to add any card to their hand. Therefore, by shuffling your opponent's hand into deck with Disturbance, they won't be able to draw/add any card afterwards, all thanks to Droll.

3) Your opponent has nothing to do but pass the turn back to you. That means you can start placing letters with "Destiny Board".

4) When it's your turn, Normal Summon Yata and attack the opponent with it, which denies your opponent from drawing any cards.

5) Repeat what was explained in #3 + #4 until you win the game with "Destiny Board".

deck_excerpt: Morphing Jar Mill OTK ft. Telefon + Emeral
deck_description:
Greetings! Here, you can experience how Empty Jar works. If you don't know how to play Telefon decks, you can check these guides!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw your whole Main Deck and Synchro Summon Ravenous with Librarian + Pharaoh + Telefon. Then, discard Wanghu + Wattfox + Sword + MJ + MJ #2 with Ravenous and at End Phase due to large hand size. However, before that, set Igknight Reload and all Traps.

2) During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate these cards in order explained below:

  1. Igknight Reload
  2. Ravenous >>> Discard Pendulum + Any
  3. Powerful Rebirth >>> Wattfox
  4. Give and Take >>> Wanghu
  5. Reverse Reuse >>> MJ #2 as face-down and MJ as face-up
  6. All-Out Attacks

3) Here is what is going on...

  • In the first two actions, "Igknight Reload" has been activated to not let you draw any cards via MJ. Even though you couldn't reveal Pendulum Monster in your hand to shuffle it and draw cards due to Ravenous, game considers "Igknight Reload" as perfectly resolved.
  • As for the rest; Wanghu destroys Wattfox, which shuts down anything your opponent can try to break you, including hand-traps. Then, via All-Out Attacks, MJ #2 will flip face-up and you can start milling your opponent with MJ.

4) After everything is done in #2 and #3, rather than both players drawing 5 cards via MJ, only your opponent can thanks to "Igknight Reload". This step will go on until your opponent has nothing to draw and you win the game!

deck_excerpt: Zoodiac loaner deck from the April 2025 Duel Triangle event.
deck_description:
Loaner deck from the April 2025 Duel Triangle event.

Official description:

Difficulty level ☆1

The monsters in this "Zoodiac" Deck draw strength directly from their allies.

Each "Zoodiac" Xyz Monster can be Summoned by using another "Zoodiac" monster (with a different name) as the material, also gaining ATK/DEF equal to that of all "Zoodiac" monsters it has attached. What's more, the Level 4 "Zoodiac" monsters have effects that grant an effect to the Xyz Monster they are attached to.

The key to winning is being attentive while using effects at all-or-nothing moments.

deck_name: Dark Souls BUT MUTATED by NUCLEAR REACTOR! (The Phantom Knights Materiactor)
deck_description: Phantom Knights + Materiactor Deck I made as an experiment for a friend cause they wanted to try a phantom knights deck and i thought materiactors could help it run lol.

Experimenting with the Mathmech engine to add further disruptions/combo lines in case my opponent has disruptions. The deck is pretty standard, running the usual @Ignisters including Bururu and Danmari for extra disruption. Danmari can be used with Singularity as it's a Link-6 and Bururu is a good search off of Wicckid for getting the ideal end board, being able to bring back an @Ignister used as synchro material. For this reason, I am running 3x Backup @Ignister so I don't have to search it and it's just really strong. While the Mathmech package can be interfered with your Achichi/Pikari normal summon, you can special summon the Diameter off of Desavewurm as part of your combo or discard for Cynet Mining/Backup @Ignister. While there isn't much space for cards like I:P Masquerena and your combos use up most of your extra deck, Singularity can shuffle them back to be re-used. It's also fine since you can banish your cards and bring them back with @Ignister trap or bring them back with A.I.dle Reborn. I'm also experimenting with Code of Soul as an additional special summon while also being able to Link summon on your opponent's turn. Since Bystials are really common in the meta to counter Memento, Blue-Eyes, mb Ryzeal and other decks, Factorial may not fully resolve properly (As you may only get 2 mathmechs on board from its eff), so Code of Soul is a backup plan that can let me link into a recycled Transcode Talker or smth else.

The full end board consists of 2 possibilities. The first is Singularity + Factorial + Ignis Trap + Danmari + Desavewurm (4 bounces, Laplacian disruption + Diameter negate, 2-3 on-board negates with the trap, 1 omni-negate targetting a card on board, and 1 Spell/Trap negate) and the 2nd is the Accode line.

Overall, I think the Main/Extra decks are solid but the side deck is questionable as I'm not good with side decks. I mostly built it for countering Maliss, Memento, and Odion but Evenly/Lightning Strike can bait out your opp's field spell negate against the Ryzeal matchup, and Dimension Ground can deal with a couple of decks like the mirror matchup. Belle can be anything like Fuwalos and you could take off 1 Lightning Storm to run 3.

deck_excerpt: Kashtira Fiendsmith Ryzeal  / Edmonton WCQ Regional Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Jesse H

Tournament: Edmonton WCQ Regional – April 12th 2025

Placement: Top 8

This is just a pretty basic Madolche deck that I’ve been experimenting with online and at locals. It’s heavily based on MBT’s most recent TMT version of the deck, but I’ve taken some of my own liberties with it. I feel like there are some differences between this and a more “traditional” Madolche deck, especially post INFO. For one, I’ve chosen to run one copy of Magileine instead of two. This is mainly because I wanted to make space for more handtraps to make the deck a little more resilient. She is a searchable target through Mini Meowcaroons and can then be normal summoned via the effect of Salon. Otherwise, she is a helpful starter, but not as valuable as Anjelly or Petingcesseour. I’ve also chosen to run Salon at two instead of one because I think the increased likelihood of opening it or drawing it makes up for running the second copy as a pseudo-brick. It also insulates first turn plays from Ash Blossom a little by reducing the necessity of adding Salon via Messengelato to get the extra Madolche normal summoned it facilitates. This also allows the option of searching for Ticket or any other Madolche spell/trap where you would have searched Salon. I’ve excluded Puddingcess, partly because of her bricky nature but also because I wanted more room for handtraps and felt that she did not come up in as many games as I would have liked. She is fine, maybe even good in the deck since she combos with Petingcesseour to go into a Madolche rank four and rank up into Puddingcess Chocolat-a-la-Mode and gain her additional effect to special summon from the deck and otherwise facilitates the summon of any two material Madolche extra deck summon with Petingcesseour (which can come in handy in simplified game states or boards that just need a bit of cleanup). However, I’ve chosen to pass on this utility to be able to make the deck more resilient going second and therefore more robust overall. Definitely feel free to cut the extra Salon for her, I may end up doing just that in the future anyway. The two Gravedigger’s Trap Holes are to enable Traptrix Rafflesia to protect against Nibiru, one of the archetype’s biggest weaknesses. The idea is simple enough, get any two level fours on board and go into Rafflesia while staying at or under five summons. To this end, it is imperative to not use Petingcesseour’s second effect before you summon Rafflesia (if you found a line where the latter’s summon is possible) or you simply will not be able to because of Petingcesseour’s archetypal lock. The revival effects of the Vernusylphs and the extra Madolche normal summon from Salon should help to this end. Sometimes it will only be possible to make Rafflesia or execute the full Madolche combo, but not both (to my current understanding of combo lines and synergies), in which case it is up to the discretion of the player on how to proceed. One of the extra deck slots, the second Fresh Sistart or S:P Little Knight, can be substituted for another generic rank four, like Exciton Knight, Bagooska, or even Dugares. Any of these options (realistically the first two) can be summoned instead of Rafflesia if the above situation comes to pass. She can also help against other hand traps, but Nibiru is the most prevalent one that should always be kept in mind. I’ve chosen to use two Gravedigger’s Trap Holes simply because Rafflesia has two materials and three could be bricky. Everything else should be pretty standard. Kashtira Fenrir is a good option going second, and can be discarded with a Vernusylph for their effects. The side deck is nothing special and is just what I feel is generally good or okay into the format. The hand trap selection is also basic, Ash Blossom and Droll to prevent adding/summoning from deck, Infinite Impermanence for effect negation, Fuwalos to deter combo decks that cannot play around or through it from making too large of an end board. Watch out for Nibiru, of course, I’ve been stopped cold too many times by the big rock, losing me games that could have otherwise been won. Droll & Lock Bird is also very annoying to play through, but not impossible. These “Drolled” lines would just have you summon and set cards from deck to build as strong a board as possible, albeit at a lower ceiling than normal. Ash Blossom definitely hurts, especially considering how much adding cards and special summoning from the deck gets done, but it is still possible to play through an “Ashed” line. Where it really hurts is when used in response to the Vernusylph cards. This will not only halt your searches but it will also prevent you from summoning an earth attribute monster from grave which can really hurt lines where you try to play around Nibiru safely, sometimes rendering them impossible. Ghost Belle is a slightly more niche counter to this deck, interrupting the graveyard shuffling effects or even Hootcake’s banish condition. I think it’s less likely to come up, but something that should still be kept in mind. Mulcharmy Fuwalos and Purulia are also annoying here, Fuwalos being the worst of the two, but not world ending. Just play accordingly and as low to the ground as needed. Effect Veiler, Infinite Impermanence, and Ghost Ogre can be annoying, possibly even turn ending if paired with another handtrap, but a lower ceiling endbord should still be possible while playing in the aftermath of those cards’ activation. Some madolche effects are non-once per turn, and can be activated again with some clever play and steering. That’s basically it! Feel free to make whatever substitutions, inclusions, or exclusions you like. I’ve already listed some options as far as that goes. If you’ve read this far, thank you and I hope you found this information useful. Best of luck!

deck_excerpt: ABC, XYZ, LIGHT, Cyber Dragon, Therion, Ancient Fairy Dragon, A to Z
deck_description:
The classic ABC deck, featuring ABC Dragon Buster and Cyber Dragon Infinity, polished and ceiling raised.

Sadly we still didn't get an errata for Union Carrier, but we got the Union support from Maze Of The Master, which means Platinum Gadget into Union Controller is doing even more for us, if we can refrain from using anything but LIGHT Extra Deck monsters.

This is obviously the bonkers going first version of the deck, making 6-7 interruptions on turn 1, but honestly it makes it easier for me to sideboard, as many of the over-the-top going first cards are an easy choice to side out for the non engine options when expecting to go second, without damaging the consistency.

You can choose to play 40 cards by cutting the AFD engine, removing Dragon Ravine and Destrudo if you find the discard for Ravine to costy or can't find your non engine pieces. I like the versatility of it, since it allows you access to Hangar and Therion in almost every game. Also the additional Summon from hand from AFD gives you access to a ton of additional bodies (when playing the 2nd Y).

With the new X, Y and Z pieces we can use Galaxy Photon Dragon to search for the Galaxy Soldiers and not miss out on any B triggers. You actually have to keep an eye on your open zones though, since they can easily clog up, blocking access to Infinity or activating the Union monsters equipped with Regulus. The Progleo in the Extra Deck might seem an odd choice, but it is a LIGHT Link 2 with arrows to the sides, so you can keep linking your ABC pieces off after starting with a herald that you might want to keep, and also allows you to recover used Link monsters using the abundance of monsters in the later stages of the game or even mid combo after getting interrupted. It might even sometimes sneakily steal an opponent's Link monster if used cleverly.

I'm not really into competitive play again yet, so the side deck might need some adjusting, but I feel like Dark Ruler and Evenly can help pierce through most boards, especially when accessible through Triple Tactics, although I'm not sure if Lancea is actually more impactful than Droll right now, but that's obviously dependant on the format and local deck distribution.

Either way: ABC is back baby! And I'm stoked to jam them at locals again.

deck_excerpt: Battlewasp Beetrooper. No Scary Moth. V1.0.
deck_description:
Still a highly experimental build. Only really posting this because I want to do some test hands. I want to experiment with running more Ragnaraika/Beetrooper monsters, since I feel like more starters might be needed. Not a handtrap version, although you could certainly run that. The deck pairs well with boardbreakers, thus I'll do that.

Main weakness of the deck is Nibiru, the Primal Being, so watch out for that.

EDIT: Forgot to mention. Running Wisteria of Woe to try to think over how well it hits Fiendsmith (along with Blue-eyes), as that's what I would see as the main threat. The deck really likes to banish, and can recycle from there very well, so I'm not particularly worried about Maliss (especially because Gran Partisan is a good card).
Trying to make a little mixture of bystial and Horus cards in it
Too early to make another Musketeer deck but its too fun ngl

deck_excerpt: Maliss with @ignister, Bystial, and a little Codetalker support.
deck_description: Maliss with @ignister and Bystial and Codetalker support. This deck is surely to do good against most decks it has been tested for good momentum. The side deck has metaltronus and detonator in side for Ryzeal matchups, Lancea for mirror matches, and Fuwalos in the side also for the extra draws when going second, Crossout also for mirror matches and if your opponent plays similar cards, Lightning Storm and Harpie's Feather Duster to counter backrow heavy decks.

Mainly built to stunk lock other players & lock up board based off " barrier" name.

can switch off cards from main deck & side deck

trench is good to use if you have 5 * or higher monster in hand or combo it with Generald's to get board up quicker!

a few additions in deck but its mainly ice barrier other monster help fill missing gap/negates.
Just something I mashed together to try the format with the cards that I currently have. If you have any comments, we can talk about it c:
